<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-03-24T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-03-24T01:00:00-05:00" n="668" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d668">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/4860: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="#p_JNT1" type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-03-24T14:00:00+08:00">March 24, 1932—2
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 24—5:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>My March 23, 1 p.m.<note n="27" xml:id="d668fn27">Not printed.</note></p>
                        <list>
                            <label>1.</label>
                            <item>Japanese and Chinese delegates met at 10 a.m. today in the
                                presence of self, <persName corresp="#p_LSMW1">Sir Miles</persName>,
                                Italian Chargé d’Affaires <persName corresp="#p_CCG1">Count
                                    Ciano</persName> and Monsieur <persName corresp="#p_BT2">Baudet</persName> representing French Minister who was
                                ill.</item>
                            <label>2.</label>
                            <item><persName corresp="#p_ULGK1">General Uyeda</persName> presented
                                new draft, text of which follows later. Discussion lasted until
                                12:40 p.m. when adjournment was made until 3 p.m. today.</item>
                            <label>3.</label>
                            <item>Japanese are insisting on agreement containing reference to gunmen
                                and to cessation of agitation by forces of the two countries.
                                Chinese disclaim all knowledge of activities of gunmen and refuse to
                                consider political questions claiming that discussion must be
                                limited under League resolution March 4th to cessation of
                                hostilities and withdrawal of Japanese troops.</item>
                            <label>4.</label>
                            <item>Atmosphere friendly but progress will be slow.</item>
                        </list>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_JNT1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>